Catalysts based on metal nanocrystals always suffer from particle aggregation or poisoning by the reaction product in liquid-phase reactions [35]. In this work, the successive photocatalytic degradation of MB was also carried out to evaluate the stability of BP-Ag/TiO2 nanocomposite. Fig. 10
                     a and b shows the normalized absorption maximum (At/A0) of MB against the reaction time in the presence of the BP-Ag/TiO2 hybrid for three successive photocatalytic degradation cycles. We can see that all the MB photodegradation reactions finished within 85 min under >420 nm irradiation, and even about 25% of MB was degraded in 85 min under >780 nm irradiation, indicating that the ternary BP-Ag/TiO2 hybrids can maintain a steady photocatalytic activity. The corresponding plots of ln[At/A0] against the reaction time as calculated from Fig. 10a and b were shown in Fig. 10c and d. We can clearly find that all the plots display a linear evolution, which matches the pseudo-first order kinetics of the reaction. Moreover, the apparent rate constants K for the three successive reactions, as indicated by the slope of the plots, remained almost the same. The K value of BP-Ag/TiO2 nanohybrids under >420 nm irradiation is about ten times than that of under >780 nm irradiation (Fig. 11
                     ). Considering the aggregation of Ag/TiO2, we used GO to support Ag/TiO2 and compared the K values of Ag/TiO2, GO-Ag/TiO2 and BP-Ag/TiO2 in visible and NIR light (Table 1
                     ). GO, as a semimetal with zero gap, exhibits no response to visibile and NIR light, but can serve as a carrier to stabilize Ag/TiO2 on its surface. Clearly, a higher photocatalytic performance of GO-Ag/TiO2 nanocomposites was observed compared with Ag/TiO2 under visible light irradiation, which is ascribed to the high dispersion and stability of Ag/TiO2 on GO surface. While BP-Ag/TiO2 showed higher photocatalytic activity than that of GO-Ag/TiO2 in visible light, and even showed photocatalytic activity in NIR light, demonstrating that BP can effectively sensitize Ag/TiO2 nanocomposites to show excellent photocatalytic activity in visible and NIR light (Table 1).
